Using the binomial theorem, we have

$$
\begin{align*}
    (x+2a)^8 &=x^8+\binom{8}{1}(x)^7(2a)^1+...+\binom{8}{r}(x)^{(8-r)}(2a)^r+...+(2a)^8 \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}
\end{align*}
$$

We need to identify the $r^{\text{th}}$ term which includes $x^5$, hence, $r=8-5=3$,

$$
    \tag*{\textbf{(A1)}}
$$

Therefore

$$
\begin{align*}
\binom{8}{3}\big(x^{5}\big)\big(2a\big)^3 &= 56x^5 \tag*{\textbf{A1}} \\[5pt]
\end{align*}
$$

Using the formula we can evaluate the binomial coefficient

$$
\begin{align*}
    \binom{8}{3}&=\frac{8!}{3!5!}\\[6pt]
    &=56\tag*{\textbf{A1}}
\end{align*}
$$


$$
\begin{align*}
(\cancel{56})(\cancel{x^5})(8a^3) &= \cancel{56}\cancel{x^5} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}\\[9pt]
8a^3 &= 1 \\[7pt]
a^3 &= \dfrac{1}{8} \\[7pt]
&\hspace{-0.535em}\tcbhighmath{a = \dfrac{1}{2}}\tag*{\textbf{A1}}
\end{align*}
$$

- We have

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  (2n-1)^3 &= (2n)^3 - 3(2n)^2 + 3(2n) - 1 \hspace{2em} \\[6pt]
  &= 8n^3 - 12n^2 + 6n - 1\end{aligned}
  $$

  and

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  (2n+1)^3 &= (2n)^3 + 3(2n)^2 + 3(2n) + 1 \hspace{2em} \\[6pt]
  &= 8n^3 + 12n^2 + 6n + 1\end{aligned}
  $$

  Summing our expressions for $(2n-1)^3$ and $(2n+1)^3$, we get

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  (2n-1)^3 + (2n+1)^3 &= 8n^3 - \cancel{12n^2} + 6n - \cancel{1} + 8n^3 + \cancel{12n^2} + 6n + \cancel{1}
  \end{aligned}
  $$

  Hence we get

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  \answer{(2n-1)^3 + (2n+1)^3 = 16n^3 + 12n} \hspace{2em}\end{aligned}
  $$

- Let $2n-1$ and $2n+1$ be two consecutive odd integers for some
$n \in \mathbb{Z}$.
  The sum of the cubes of $2n-1$ and $2n+1$ is

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  \hspace{6.4em} (2n-1)^3 + (2n+1)^3 &= 16n^3 + 12n \hspace{2em} [\text{by part (a)}] \\[6pt]
  &= 4n(4n^2 + 3) \hspace{2.22em} [\text{multiple of $4$}]\end{aligned}
  $$

  Hence the sum of the cubes of any two consecutive odd integers is
divisible by four.

From the formula booklet we can find the formula for a general term of the expansion

$$
\begin{align*}
    (a+b)^n&=...+\binom{n}{r}a^{n-r}b^r+...
\end{align*}
$$

Using the general term above, we can write an expression for the $x^3$ term and the $x^4$ term.

$$
\begin{align*}
    &\binom{6}{3}(a)^3(bx)^3& \binom{6}{4}(a)^2(bx)^4 \tag*{\textbf{A1A1}}
\end{align*}
$$

We can now use the information given to write an equation linking the coefficients of the two expressions above.

$$
\begin{align*}
    &\binom{6}{3}a^3b^3=-2\times \binom{6}{4}a^2b^4 \tag*{\textbf{M1}}
\end{align*}
$$

Using the formula we can evaluate the binomial coefficients and simplify

$$
\begin{align*}
    \textcolor{white}{hack} \tag*{\textbf{M1}}
\end{align*}
$$


$$
\begin{align*}
    \frac{6!}{3!3!}a^3b^3&=-2\times \frac{6!}{4!2!}a^2b^4\\[6pt]
    \frac{6\times 5 \times 4\times \cancel{3!}}{\cancel{3!}\times3\times 2\times 1}a^3b^3&=-2\times \frac{6\times 5 \times  \cancel{4!}}{\cancel{4!}\times 2 \times 1}a^2b^4\\[6pt]
    20a^3b^3&=-30a^2b^4 \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
\end{align*}
$$

We need to find the value of $\tfrac{a}{b}$ therefore we can rearrange the expression above

$$
\begin{align*}
    \frac{a^3b^3}{a^2b^4}&=\frac{-30}{20}\\[6pt]
    \frac{a}{b}&=\hspace{0.525em}\tcbhighmath{\frac{-3}{2}}\tag*{\textbf{A1}}\\[6pt]
    &=-1.5
\end{align*}
$$

Because each term in the expansion of $(x+a)^7$ will be divided by $bx$, we require the terms in $x^6$ and $x^4$. Using the Binomial Theorem, we have

$$
\begin{align*}
    \text{Term in $x^6$} &= \binom{7}{1}x^6a \\[8pt]
    &= 7x^6a \\[8pt]
    \text{Term in $x^4$} &= \binom{7}{3}x^4a^3 \\[8pt]
    &= 35x^4a^3
\end{align*}
$$

Dividing both these terms by $bx$ we get

$$
\begin{align*}
    \dfrac{7x^6a}{bx} &= \dfrac{7x^5a}{b} \\[8pt]
    \dfrac{35x^4a^3}{bx} &= \dfrac{35x^3a^3}{b}
\end{align*}
$$

Given that the coefficient of $x^5$ is $2$, and the coefficient of $x^3$ is $1690$, we have

$$
\begin{align*}
    \dfrac{7a}{b} &= 2 \\[8pt]
    \dfrac{35a^3}{b} &= 1690
\end{align*}
$$

And therefore

$$
\begin{align*}
    7a &= 2b \tag*{[1]}\\[8pt] 
    35a^3 &= 1690b \tag*{[2]}
\end{align*}
$$

Dividing equation [2] by equation [1] we have

$$
\begin{align*}
    \dfrac{35a^3}{7a} &= \dfrac{1690b}{2b} \\[8pt]
    5a^2 &= 845 \\[8pt]
    a^2 &= 169 \\[8pt]
    a &= \pm 13
\end{align*}
$$

Given that $a>0$, $\tcbhighmath{a = 13}$. Substituting into equation [1],

$$
\begin{align*}
    7a &= 2b \\[8pt]
    7(13) &= 2b \\[8pt]
    &\hspace{-0.5em}\tcbhighmath{b = 45.5}
\end{align*}
$$

- The process of rewriting a single fraction as two (or more!) fractions is known as partial fractions.
  Let's setup an identity using the information given, this means the identity is true for all valid values of $x$.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \dfrac{3x-7}{3x^2+x-2} &\equiv \dfrac{A}{x+1}+\dfrac{B}{3x-2}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  We can then multiply throughout by $3x^2+x-2$ to get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      3x-7&= (3x-2)A+(x+1)B\tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Next expand the R.H.S. and then collect together the coefficients of $x$ and the constant

  $$
   \begin{align*}
      3x-7&=3Ax-2A+Bx+B\\[6pt]
      3x-7&=(3A+B)x-2A+B
  \end{align*}
  $$

  We can now equate the coefficients of $x$ and the constant term, to form two equations

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      3A+B&=3\\[6pt]
      -2A+B&=-7
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Subtracting the two equations gives

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      5A&=10\\[6pt]
      A&=2
  \end{align*}
  $$

  And

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      3(2)+B&=3\\[6pt]
      B&=-3\\[6pt]
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Hence we have

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \dfrac{3x-7}{3x^2+x-2}&=\dfrac{2}{x+1}-\dfrac{3}{3x-2}\\[8pt]
      &=\answer{\dfrac{2}{x+1}+\left(-\dfrac{3}{3x-2}\right)}\hspace{1em}\text{[In the form required]}\tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- First we can rewrite both quotients in index form

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      2(x+1)^{-1}- 3(3x-2)^{-1}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Next consider the given formula for the extension of the binomial theorem

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      (a+b)^n&=a^n\left(1+n\left(\frac{b}{a}\right)+\frac{n(n-1)}{2!}\left(\frac{b}{a}\right)^2+...\right)
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Let's begin with the first quotient

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      2(x+1)^{-1}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  We can see that $a=1$, $b=x$ and $n=-1$, hence the first three terms are

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      2(x+1)^{-1}&=2\times 1^{-1}\left(1+(-1)\left(\frac{x}{1}\right)+\frac{-1((-1)-1)}{2!}\left(\frac{x}{1}\right)^2\right)\\[12pt]
      &=2-2x+2x^2\tag*{\textbf{(A1)}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Now lets consider the other quotient

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      -3(3x-2)^{-1}
  \end{align*}  
  $$

  This one is not as straight forward.
  In order to use the formula effectively it is best to try and rewrite the quotient by factorising out the $a^n$ term, this is the constant term inside the bracket

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      -3(3x-2)^{-1}&=-3(-2\left(-\tfrac{3}{2}x+1\right))^{-1}\\[6pt]
      &=-3 \times (-2)^{-1}\left(1-\tfrac{3}{2}x\right)^{-1}\\[6pt]
      &=\tfrac{3}{2}\left(1-\tfrac{3}{2}x\right)^{-1}
  \end{align*}   
  $$

  In this form we can now see that $a=1$, $b=-\tfrac{3}{2}x$ and $n=-1$, hence we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \tfrac{3}{2}\left(1-\tfrac{3}{2}x\right)^{-1}&=\tfrac{3}{2}\left(1+(-1)\left(-\tfrac{3}{2}x\right)+\frac{-1((-1)-1)}{2!}\left(-\tfrac{3}{2}x\right)^2\right)\tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}\\[12pt]
      &=\tfrac{3}{2}\left(1+\tfrac{3}{2}x+\tfrac{9}{4}x^2\right)\\[12pt]
      &=\tfrac{3}{2}+\tfrac{9}{4}x+\tfrac{27}{8}x^2\tag*{\textbf{(A1)}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Hence we need to sum the two results which gives

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      2(x+1)^{-1}- 3(3x-2)^{-1}&=2-2x+2x^2+\tfrac{3}{2}+\tfrac{9}{4}x+\tfrac{27}{8}x^2\tag*{\textbf{M1}}\\[6pt]
      &=\answer{\frac{7}{2}+\tfrac{1}{4}x+\tfrac{43}{8}x^2}\tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}    
  $$

