We have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\sqrt{\dfrac{1+x}{1-x}} &= (1+x)^{\frac{1}{2}}(1-x)^{-\frac{1}{2}}\end{aligned}
$$

Using the fractional binomial theorem, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\hspace{3em} (1+x)^{\frac{1}{2}} &= \sum_{k=0}^\infty \binom{\scriptstyle{1/2}}{k} x^k \hspace{3em} \big[|x| < 1\big] \\[3pt]
&= 1 + \bigg(\dfrac{1}{2}\bigg)x + \bigg(\dfrac{1}{2}\bigg)\bigg(\dfrac{1}{2}-1\bigg)\dfrac{x^2}{2!} + \cdots \\[7pt]
&= 1 + \dfrac{x}{2} - \dfrac{x^2}{8} + \cdots\end{aligned}
$$

Using the
fractional binomial theorem, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\hspace{6.8em} (1-x)^{-\frac{1}{2}} &= \sum_{k=0}^\infty \binom{\scriptstyle{-1/2}}{k} (-x)^k \hspace{3em} \big[|x| < 1\big] \\[3pt]
&= 1 + \left(\hspace{-0.3em}-\dfrac{1}{2}\right)\hspace{-0.2em}(-x) + \left(\hspace{-0.3em}-\dfrac{1}{2}\right)\hspace{-0.2em}\left(\hspace{-0.3em}-\dfrac{1}{2}-1\right)\hspace{-0.2em}\dfrac{(-x)^2}{2!} + \cdots \\[7pt]
&= 1 + \dfrac{x}{2} + \dfrac{3x^2}{8} + \cdots\end{aligned}
$$

Hence we get

$$
\begin{aligned}
\hspace{1.7em} (1+x)^{\frac{1}{2}}(1-x)^{-\frac{1}{2}} &= \bigg[1 + \dfrac{x}{2} - \dfrac{x^2}{8} + \cdots\bigg]\bigg[1 + \dfrac{x}{2} + \dfrac{3x^2}{8} + \cdots\bigg] \\[6pt]
&= \left\{

\begin{array}{rccccl}
1 &+& \dfrac{x}{2} &+& \dfrac{3x^2}{8} & + \cdots \\[12pt]
&+& \dfrac{x}{2} &+& \dfrac{x^2}{4} & + \cdots \\[12pt]
&  &                    &-& \dfrac{x^2}{8} & + \cdots \\[12pt]
\end{array}\right. \\[6pt]
&= 1 + x + \dfrac{x^2}{2} + \cdots \end{aligned}
$$

For $|x| < 1$, the
term in $x^k$ is small for $k \geq 3$.
Hence we deduce

$$
\begin{aligned}
\answer{\sqrt{\dfrac{1+x}{1-x}} \approx 1 + x + \dfrac{x^2}{2}} \hspace{3em} \big[|x| < 1\big]\end{aligned}
$$
